⚔️Crafting ⚔️

Info you should know, thanks my brother @bestyet2come_ 

511,383 play at the HIGH SCHOOL LEVEL
64,052 Play college ball
Odds of making a NCAA D1 roster = 43:1

11.7 Scholarships for 30 to 40 guys at every level except D3

43:1 Chances of an NYC player making  a D1 roster 

Route with the biggest chances in percentage go as follows:

1 Highschool pProspect: (Usually has the most leverage)

2 JUCO: Gives you college exposure and prepares you for your four year. Still decent leverage. You play for two years and develop instead of sitting the bench like most schools do to players until their junior year (Where you will battle that JUCO transfer anyways) 

3. D1: School in a respected conference.... Get picked up Junior YEAR.. if you don’t, you lose your leverage to the younger guys and international draft for any chance at money. Best chance is free agency which gives no draft protection. Can get released one day after the next. 

Anything else gives you an extreme odd of
2.1 % for D2
 sub 1% for D3 and NAIA.

DO not believe words BELIEVE FACTS!!!!!

The numbers don’t lie and never will. Understand what you’re up against, what ever you think is enough it just is not!!!!!

All information comes directly from the NCAA WEBSITE.

Why are hitting drills important? 

Hitting a baseball is arguably (as Ted Williams was known to say) the most difficult thing to do in sports.  You’re dealing with baseballs thrown at different speeds, in different locations, and moving different directions.  This is a challenge – to say the least. 

That is why one minor flaw, loss of rhythm, or the slightest timing issue will throw off your swing and make hitting even more difficult.

Identify what piece of your swing needs improvement and look for a drill that focuses and isolates that problem area.  Repeatedly and correctly working on your deficiency will eventually make your swing better.

The Batting Tee 

In a game you have to deal with what the pitcher is throwing at you as well as how your swing feels that day.  Using a tee is the only way you are 100% in control of your swing.  There are no external factors you have to deal with (type of pitch, location, etc). 

When you need to work out kinks in your swing I think you would want to be in 100% control.   Once you establish some consistency off a tee you can move to some type of underhand flip and then into batting practice.
